			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><div class="postbody">Here is a long but really interesting article about Iraq debt.  A couple interesting points.  
<br />
More than half of Iraq's debt is reparations.  
<br />
Iraq's per capita debt is 10x greater than Argentina's was in 2001.
<br />
Germany's debt after WWI was about 2x its GDP.  This was a major factor in the build up to WWII.  Iraq's debt is 15x its GDP.
<br />
Iraq made no attempts to service its debt in the 1990s.
<br />
Iraq's entire oil production in the 1990s would not have even met the interest charges.
<br />

<br />
The debt forgiveness is a necessary thing.  However, why come up with it now?  It seems a decade late. Would it have been possible to deal with this issue while Hussein was in power?  How else could Hussein have been removed? Should the Shi'ites have been given more support for an uprising in the early 1990s? Should we have dealt with Hussein in the 1980s when he was conducting genocide on the Kurds? Should we have gone to Bagdad in 1991? Should we have told Hussein not to invade Kuwait and that it wouldn't be viewed as a "local" matter and kept him as our buddy? Are the possible futures of the Middle East worth putting it off and inflicting a war on the area?
<br />

<br />
Give the article a read.  It is quite interesting.
<br />
<a href="http://www.ccc.nps.navy.mil/rsepResources/si/june03/middleEast.asp" target="_blank">http://www.ccc.nps.navy.mil/rsepResources/si/june03/middleEast.asp</a><span class="gensmall"></span>


				</div></td>
			</tr>
