				<td colspan="2"><div class="postbody">rove and bush are "rapturists." The rapturist heresy is one marked by partly:
<br />
1- (theological) a denial of the redemption and resurection of Christ.
<br />
2- (joint secular and theological) a compelling belief that things must crash and burn, as per Revelations.
<br />
3- (secular) that the <span style="font-style: italic">Saved</span> will not remain on the earth to repay debts.
<br />

<br />
The Book of Revelations is to be taken literally by them, and if it God ain't doing it fast enough, then they will <span style="font-style: italic">bring it on</span> themselves. Armageddon is supposed to take place in the Middle East, so that is where the army needs to be sent. And part of why North Korea won't see anything more than American sabre rattling: it is not covered in either the New or Old Testaments and therefore irrelevant.
<br />

<br />
Issue 1: Rapturists believe that they won't die. Death scares them, so they will be swept up to heaven while still living. Death and resurrection don't apply to them. Its Jesus come save us. Maybe they want several extra shots at entry into Heaven. This denies Christian theology and is why it is heretical. The sermon on the mount does not apply to them, <span style="font-style: italic">turn the other cheek</span> is for targets, they want more than <span style="font-style: italic">an eye for an eye</span>. 
<br />

<br />
Issue 2: Clean Air Acts and  Environmental Protection laws are evil to rapturists because they slow down the introduction of the <span style="font-style: italic">End Times</span>. "Who are we to interfere with God's Will" is a common statement from a rapturist. Jeremiah, Daniel and Revelations all tell of pretty bad times, <span style="font-style: italic">bring them on</span>. Maybe there is something that can be done to hurry it along? Like tax subsidies for SUVs? Dieing coral reefs, melting polar caps and overfishing are not a call to action, but something to be rejoiced as a sign of the upcoming <span style="font-style: italic">End Times</span>. The only way to save the forest is to cut it down. Global warming? Umm, rev8.7: The first angel blew his trumpet, and there followed hail and fire mixed with blood, which fell on the earth; and a third part of the earth was burnt up, and a third of the trees were burnt up, and all green grass was burnt up. Warming and burnt up, ok, thats in the Bible, therfore it is good, <span style="font-style: italic">bring it on</span>. Acid rain? well, rev 8.11: A third of the waters turned bitter, and many people died from the waters that had become bitter. Well, that sounds close enough, <span style="font-style: italic">bring it on</span>.
<br />

<br />
Issue 3: Repayment of the National Debt, or rebuilding of destroyed nations is unnecessary, since only the unbelievers will be left, so @#%$ them, no, wait, they commit adultery, so let them @#%$ themselves. Cut taxes so we can dance around, the bill won't come due for the faithful. But we extended copyrights so that when we get brought back to the Post-Rapture Earth, we will still own the rights to Mickey Mouse, and collect the royalties from the unbelievers that were stuck here. YeeeeHaw!
<br />

<br />
Counter-Issue 1: If that car will be unmanned in the event of rapture, can I have it?
<br />
Counter-Issue 2: <a href="http://www.creationcare.org/" target="_blank" class="postlink">Faith based environmentalism</a>
<br />
Counter-Issue 3: They don't believe that they will be around to foot the bill for their spending, but what will be the cost to them if they are wrong in predicting the exact end? What will be the cost to the rest of us? Better use mini-max and maxi-min to determine the worst case scenarios.<span class="gensmall"></span>


